WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.919 --> 00:00:03.330
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.330 --> 00:00:06.720
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:10.580
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:10.580 --> 00:00:15.340
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:15.340 --> 00:00:16.520
of videos.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:18.400
Thanks for your help.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:23.980
In this lab we will practice some basic configurations
on a Cisco Wireless LAN Controller to set

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:26.539
up a simple wireless LAN.

00:00:26.539 --> 00:00:31.119
Although the WLC in packet tracer is limited,
it’s good enough to practice what you need

00:00:31.119 --> 00:00:32.809
to for the CCNA.

00:00:32.809 --> 00:00:38.309
Note that, in this lab I have pre-configured
the switch, and more importantly I have done

00:00:38.309 --> 00:00:44.030
the initial setup of the wireless LAN controller
so we can access the GUI.

00:00:44.030 --> 00:00:49.269
In packet tracer you can’t access the console
port of the WLC, so to do the initial setup

00:00:49.269 --> 00:00:51.760
you have to use the packet tracer GUI.

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:55.329
Honestly it was a bit frustrating to get it
working properly.

00:00:55.329 --> 00:01:00.879
So, to make this video go smoothly the initial
setup has been pre-configured.

00:01:00.879 --> 00:01:05.170
By initial setup, I mean the setup I did in
the CLI of the wireless LAN controller in

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:06.320
the lecture video.

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:12.770
So, now we can actually access the WLC GUI
and set up some wireless LANs.

00:01:12.770 --> 00:01:17.130
Note that in the lab file I will share with
you, the initial setup is complete too.

00:01:17.130 --> 00:01:22.929
So, if you want to do the initial setup yourself
when using my lab file, just delete the current

00:01:22.929 --> 00:01:28.820
WLC, go to the wireless devices section down
here and add a new WLC.

00:01:28.820 --> 00:01:32.109
I used the 3504.

00:01:32.109 --> 00:01:39.259
So, before going into the GUI of the WLC,
let’s just take a quick look at the switch

00:01:39.259 --> 00:01:41.200
config.

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:43.140
ENABLE.

00:01:43.140 --> 00:01:44.580
SHOW RUN.

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:49.490
Okay, so like in the lecture video I will
use the switch as a DHCP server.

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:53.670
Note that I configured some excluded address
ranges.

00:01:53.670 --> 00:01:57.530
This is generally a good practice when configuring
DHCP.

00:01:57.530 --> 00:02:01.850
Even if you don’t need them now, you might
want to assign a static IP address to some

00:02:01.850 --> 00:02:03.720
devices in the future.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:07.689
Okay, and down below we have the DHCP pools
themselves.

00:02:07.689 --> 00:02:13.310
We have the VLAN10 pool, which will be used
to give IP addresses to the APs, as well as

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:18.370
PC1 which we will use to access the GUI of
the WLC.

00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:25.019
Note that I added option 43, which will tell
the APs the IP address of their WLC.

00:02:25.019 --> 00:02:30.120
As I explained in the lecture video, in this
network it actually isn’t necessary.

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:34.870
When the APs boot up they will send broadcast
CAPWAP messages to check if there are any

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:37.580
WLCs on the local network.

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:43.590
In this case WLC1 is connected to the same
local network as AP1 and AP2, so it should

00:02:43.590 --> 00:02:45.460
reply to their broadcasts.

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:47.750
No need for this option 43.

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:53.810
Anyway, then we have DHCP pools for VLAN100
and VLAN200.

00:02:53.810 --> 00:02:58.790
These pools will be used for the wireless
clients using the Internal and Guest SSIDs.

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:05.629
Okay, looking down a bit more we have the
three VLANs, management, internal, and guest.

00:03:05.629 --> 00:03:08.160
And here are the interfaces.

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:13.489
Note that this time I setup the WLC to not
tag traffic in the management VLAN, and I

00:03:13.489 --> 00:03:20.439
also configured the management VLAN, VLAN10,
as the native VLAN on SW1’s G1/0/1 interface.

00:03:20.439 --> 00:03:23.909
So, management traffic won’t be tagged.

00:03:23.909 --> 00:03:28.569
You can choose to tag or not tag the traffic,
but make sure it’s the same on both the

00:03:28.569 --> 00:03:33.019
WLC side and the switch side, or else they
won’t be able to communicate.

00:03:33.019 --> 00:03:41.690
G1/0/2, 3, and 4, connected to the APs and
PC1, are access ports in VLAN10.

00:03:41.690 --> 00:03:46.410
Okay and after the physical interfaces we
can see that SW1 has an interface for each

00:03:46.410 --> 00:03:48.390
VLAN as well.

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:53.329
Just like in the lecture video, I have designed
the network so that SW1’s SVIs will be the

00:03:53.329 --> 00:03:56.180
default gateway for hosts in each of the subnets.

00:03:56.180 --> 00:04:01.490
Note that I didn’t add these MAC-ADDRESS
commands myself, they were added automatically

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:03.629
by packet tracer.

00:04:03.629 --> 00:04:08.980
Okay, that was a brief overview of the switch’s
configurations, mostly the same as in the

00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:10.620
lecture video.

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:13.770
Now I’ll switch over to PC1.

00:04:13.770 --> 00:04:17.100
From the desktop tab, click on ‘web browser’.

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:21.120
And now let’s access the GUI of the WLC.

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:26.180
Note that, with the model of WLC I’m using,
I have to use HTTPS.

00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:30.870
It doesn’t allow HTTP connections by default.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:36.190
So, HTTPS://172.16.1.10.

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:43.290
Okay, here is the login screen of the WLC,
let’s login.

00:04:43.290 --> 00:04:56.790
The username is admin, and the password is
Cisco123, with a capital C.

00:04:56.790 --> 00:04:59.080
And here we are, the GUI.

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:03.510
This is actually very accurate, and exploring
the GUI in packet tracer is a great way to

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:07.260
get familiar with it and prepare for the exam.

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:13.020
Of course, the functionality is quite limited,
but it’s more than enough for the CCNA level.

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:18.540
You can see which interface SW1 is connected
to, it’s port 1 which is green here.

00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:23.640
And if we scroll down, we can see that the
two APs have already joined with the WLC.

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:26.590
However there aren’t any clients at the
moment.

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:33.060
So, in step 2 I say to spend some time familiarizing
yourself with the WLC GUI.

00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:37.910
By that I mean just look around each tab and
see what information you can find, what settings

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:40.190
you can configure, etc.

00:05:40.190 --> 00:05:44.560
For the sake of time we won’t spend a lot
of time looking around, but for example here’s

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:46.590
one handy feature.

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:59.130
From this default monitor tab, click on statistics
and then AP join.

00:05:59.130 --> 00:06:04.150
Here you can see the APs that have joined,
or tried to join, the WLC.

00:06:04.150 --> 00:06:08.490
You can see AP1 and AP2 here, and their status
is joined.

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:19.380
If I click on one, we can see more details.

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:24.830
This screen is very handy for troubleshooting
if an AP is unable to join the WLC.

00:06:24.830 --> 00:06:30.800
For example you can see which messages were
exchanged by the WLC and AP when it was joining,

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:35.690
and if you scroll down you can see different
statistics, including information like ‘reason

00:06:35.690 --> 00:06:39.470
for last unsuccessful attempt’ if an AP
failed to join.

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:45.220
Anyway, I recommend spending some time looking
around the WLC to get familiar, but let’s

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:47.970
move on.

00:06:47.970 --> 00:06:52.900
For step 3, let’s configure some dynamic
interfaces to be used for the internal and

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:54.100
guest WLANs.

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:57.720
That is under the controller tab.

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:00.360
Make sure you know things like that for the
exam.

00:07:00.360 --> 00:07:05.080
Know which tab to use to create or edit interfaces
on the WLC.

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:08.550
Cisco could test how familiar you are with
the GUI.

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:16.610
Okay, next I’ll click on interfaces.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:23.960
On the top right of this screen, I can create
a new interface.

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:33.830
I’ll name it Internal, and give it a VLAN
ID of 100.

00:07:33.830 --> 00:07:39.530
Then click on apply.

00:07:39.530 --> 00:07:46.530
Okay, now let’s configure it.

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:50.400
First, which physical port will be used?

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:55.930
Only one is connected, and that is port 1,
so I’ll change this to 1.

00:07:55.930 --> 00:08:06.550
Then the VLAN ID is 100, the IP address is
10.0.0.10, and I’ll configure a /24 netmask.

00:08:06.550 --> 00:08:12.400
Finally the gateway is 10.0.0.1, the SVI of
SW1.

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:17.240
Also let’s configure SW1 as the DHCP server
too, 10.0.0.1.

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:19.490
That’s all.

00:08:19.490 --> 00:08:22.970
Scroll back up, and click apply.

00:08:22.970 --> 00:08:25.750
Click past this warning, and now it’s configured.

00:08:25.750 --> 00:08:36.500
I’ll click BACK.

00:08:36.500 --> 00:08:37.500
There it is.

00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:42.719
So, the dynamic interface for the Internal
WLAN is done, so let’s make one more for

00:08:42.719 --> 00:08:45.769
the Guest WLAN.

00:08:45.769 --> 00:08:48.329
Click on New.

00:08:48.329 --> 00:09:00.080
I’ll name it Guest, and assign VLAN ID 200.

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:10.339
Then click on apply.

00:09:10.339 --> 00:09:15.870
On this screen, again the port number is 1,
the only one connected at the moment.

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:18.699
The VLAN ID is 200, that’s fine.

00:09:18.699 --> 00:09:23.759
Then the IP address is 10.1.0.10.

00:09:23.759 --> 00:09:28.620
Netmask is 255.255.255.0.

00:09:28.620 --> 00:09:33.270
Gateway is 10.1.0.1, the SVI of SW1.

00:09:33.270 --> 00:09:37.160
And once again SW1 is the DHCP server, 10.1.0.1.

00:09:37.160 --> 00:09:38.820
That’s it.

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:45.100
I’ll click on apply, and then BACK.

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:54.580
So, that’s all we need to do to create the
dynamic interfaces.

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:56.529
Pretty simple.

00:09:56.529 --> 00:09:59.720
Finally let’s create the two WLANs themselves.

00:09:59.720 --> 00:10:03.660
We can do that from the WLANs tab, of course.

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:14.050
Notice there are no WLANs at the moment.

00:10:14.050 --> 00:10:19.069
Actually in the initial setup I had to make
one, but I deleted it before starting this

00:10:19.069 --> 00:10:20.069
video.

00:10:20.069 --> 00:10:23.690
So, let’s create 2 new ones from the beginning.

00:10:23.690 --> 00:10:30.769
Click on GO here next to create new.

00:10:30.769 --> 00:10:39.300
So, the type is WLAN, this is a normal WLAN.

00:10:39.300 --> 00:10:44.670
The profile name is just a name used to identify
the WLAN in the WLC.

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:50.089
Usually you’ll just make it the same as
the SSID, so I’ll make both Internal.

00:10:50.089 --> 00:10:55.000
The ID at the bottom is a number that identifies
the WLAN in the WLC.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.690
It has to be unique, but it doesn’t matter
what it is.

00:10:57.690 --> 00:11:02.880
I’ll leave it at 1, and click Apply.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:12.390
Okay, here’s where we configure the main
settings.

00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:18.540
First, in the general tab I must enable the
WLAN, that’s very important.

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:24.490
And I also should map this WLAN to the Internal
dynamic interface, not the management interface.

00:11:24.490 --> 00:11:28.420
Okay, that’s all we need to do here on the
general tab.

00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:30.680
Next is the security tab.

00:11:30.680 --> 00:11:37.769
The CCNA exam requires us to be able to configure
WLANs using WPA2 with pre-shared key authentication.

00:11:37.769 --> 00:11:43.240
So, select WPA+WPA2 as the layer 2 security.

00:11:43.240 --> 00:11:49.850
I’ll then enable WPA2 policy here, and leave
AES encryption enabled.

00:11:49.850 --> 00:11:54.829
Next, I won’t enable 802.1X, we don’t
need that for the CCNA.

00:11:54.829 --> 00:11:58.769
Instead I’ll just enable PSK, pre-shared
key.

00:11:58.769 --> 00:12:06.029
I’ll configure it the same as the WLC password,
Cisco123 with a capital C. Okay, that’s

00:12:06.029 --> 00:12:07.029
all here.

00:12:07.029 --> 00:12:10.480
I won’t touch the layer 3 or AAA tabs.

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:14.700
Next let’s look at the QoS tab.

00:12:14.700 --> 00:12:19.270
I won’t touch anything here, actually packet
tracer doesn’t allow me to touch anything

00:12:19.270 --> 00:12:20.270
here.

00:12:20.270 --> 00:12:23.800
Even if I click on the QoS setting, the menu
doesn’t appear.

00:12:23.800 --> 00:12:29.050
As I said, the functionality is quite limited,
but at least you can look around and get familiar

00:12:29.050 --> 00:12:31.559
with the GUI.

00:12:31.559 --> 00:12:34.570
Finally I’ll look at the advanced tab.

00:12:34.570 --> 00:12:38.570
Most of this you can’t configure either,
but for example I’ll set the maximum allowed

00:12:38.570 --> 00:12:40.339
clients to 100.

00:12:40.339 --> 00:12:50.990
That’s all for now, so I’ll click Apply
to save the settings, and then click on BACK.

00:12:50.990 --> 00:13:01.910
Okay, the Internal WLAN has been created,
and notice the security policy is WPA2 with

00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:03.450
PSK authentication.

00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:04.450
Perfect.

00:13:04.450 --> 00:13:08.580
Now let’s create the Guest WLAN.

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:14.269
Click on Go.

00:13:14.269 --> 00:13:26.519
I’ll make both the profile name and SSID
guest, and then click on Apply.

00:13:26.519 --> 00:13:38.480
Make sure to enable this one too, that’s
an easy mistake to make.

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:44.269
Now let’s set the interface, which should
be Guest, which will map the Guest WLAN to

00:13:44.269 --> 00:13:46.279
the Guest dynamic interface.

00:13:46.279 --> 00:13:49.680
Next let’s move on to security.

00:13:49.680 --> 00:13:59.990
Again, select WPA+WPA2, enable WPA2 policy,
enable PSK authentication, and configure the

00:13:59.990 --> 00:14:00.990
PSK.

00:14:00.990 --> 00:14:04.800
That’s all I’ll configure for this WLAN.

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:14.870
So, click on apply, and then click on back.

00:14:14.870 --> 00:14:24.440
Okay, finally let’s add a wireless client
and associate it with an AP.

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:30.600
From the end devices section down here, I’ll
add a smart phone.

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:33.370
Now let’s make it join the Internal SSID.

00:14:33.370 --> 00:14:38.050
To do that open it up and go to the config
tab.

00:14:38.050 --> 00:14:43.329
Then click on the Wireless0 interface, this
is its WiFi radio.

00:14:43.329 --> 00:14:45.379
Note here the SSID is default.

00:14:45.379 --> 00:14:48.449
I’ll change it to Internal.

00:14:48.449 --> 00:14:51.420
Then we have to select the kind of authentication.

00:14:51.420 --> 00:14:58.879
It should be WPA2-PSK, and then the PSK pass
phrase is Cisco123.

00:14:58.879 --> 00:15:00.730
And that’s it, that’s all we have to do.

00:15:00.730 --> 00:15:04.890
Note that the IP configuration is already
set to DHCP.

00:15:04.890 --> 00:15:12.259
So, if we wait a bit it should associate with
an AP, get an IP address from SW1 via DHCP,

00:15:12.259 --> 00:15:15.250
and then be able to communicate on the network.

00:15:15.250 --> 00:15:16.759
And indeed it worked.

00:15:16.759 --> 00:15:22.370
Notice that you can see the association here
on the diagram, and also that it got an IP

00:15:22.370 --> 00:15:23.370
address.

00:15:23.370 --> 00:15:27.470
But there is a problem here, did you notice
it?

00:15:27.470 --> 00:15:30.249
Look at the IP address of the phone.

00:15:30.249 --> 00:15:35.519
Even though we’re associated with the Internal
WLAN, which is mapped to the Internal dynamic

00:15:35.519 --> 00:15:41.030
interface, which is in VLAN100 and should
get an IP address from the VLAN100 pool, it

00:15:41.030 --> 00:15:44.940
got an IP address from the VLAN10 pool, the
management subnet.

00:15:44.940 --> 00:15:49.050
Don’t worry, this isn’t a problem with
our configurations.

00:15:49.050 --> 00:15:53.399
If you did the same configurations with real
hardware, as I confirmed, the device will

00:15:53.399 --> 00:15:55.779
get an IP address from the correct pool.

00:15:55.779 --> 00:16:00.269
Packet tracer just doesn’t behave accurately,
unfortunately.

00:16:00.269 --> 00:16:01.269
But that’s okay.

00:16:01.269 --> 00:16:06.180
The goal of this lab was to practice some
basic WLAN configurations in the GUI of a

00:16:06.180 --> 00:16:09.369
Cisco WLC, and that’s what we did.

00:16:09.369 --> 00:16:14.350
That’s all for this lab, thanks for watching.

